1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:02:02,000
(Watch on www.dramacool.club Support Admin)

2
00:03:29,941 --> 00:03:34,529
A student named Charles Meliton
has compromising photographs of my friend.

3
00:03:34,737 --> 00:03:36,281
Earth to Loki?

4
00:03:40,410 --> 00:03:42,704
All the compromising photos
and files are here.

5
00:03:42,954 --> 00:03:44,581
I’m sorry for having you abducted.

6
00:03:44,789 --> 00:03:47,916
So Loki was right. You're the mastermind.

7
00:03:47,917 --> 00:03:49,001
More than half a year ago,

8
00:03:49,002 --> 00:03:51,003
my brother investigated several cases

9
00:03:51,004 --> 00:03:53,965
that connected all to one person
only known as "M."

10
00:03:54,424 --> 00:03:56,593
My classmate is missing.

11
00:03:57,719 --> 00:04:00,638
- Just picking up the trash, ma'am.
- Oh.

12
00:04:01,681 --> 00:04:03,224
John Bautista?

13
00:04:04,475 --> 00:04:07,854
You? You're the one who abducted them?

14
00:04:08,188 --> 00:04:09,814
And now it’s your turn.

15
00:04:18,740 --> 00:04:20,825
It's your turn.

16
00:04:23,828 --> 00:04:25,455
I'm begging you, please...

17
00:04:36,174 --> 00:04:37,300
Lorelei!

18
00:04:40,720 --> 00:04:41,804
Lorelei!

19
00:04:45,850 --> 00:04:46,935
Lorelei!

20
00:05:05,245 --> 00:05:08,373
Looks like we need to teach
that guy a lesson again.

21
00:05:09,165 --> 00:05:11,918
Let’s see if he still won’t learn
from this.

22
00:05:14,837 --> 00:05:16,130
She's awake.

23
00:05:29,102 --> 00:05:30,770
Is this the end for me?

24
00:05:34,983 --> 00:05:37,026
I don’t want to die yet!

25
00:05:40,780 --> 00:05:43,741
I want to achieve my dreams.

26
00:05:45,410 --> 00:05:48,079
And make more friends.

27
00:05:50,707 --> 00:05:53,293
I still want to get to know myself.

28
00:05:55,503 --> 00:05:58,255
I still want to talk to my dad.

29
00:05:58,256 --> 00:06:02,176
And I want to understand why,
after you were gone,

30
00:06:02,510 --> 00:06:04,512
he’s grown distant from me.

31
00:06:06,597 --> 00:06:09,142
I want us to make things right.

32
00:06:11,519 --> 00:06:14,188
But if this is what’s meant for me,

33
00:06:15,940 --> 00:06:17,608
there’s nothing I can do.

34
00:06:18,693 --> 00:06:21,821
No matter how I try to run,

35
00:06:22,363 --> 00:06:24,490
it will always find me.

36
00:06:25,533 --> 00:06:26,868
Is this really it?

37
00:06:28,411 --> 00:06:30,830
Is there no one left to help me?

38
00:06:34,834 --> 00:06:36,336
Oh, Loki…

39
00:06:38,254 --> 00:06:39,339
Please…

40
00:06:39,756 --> 00:06:41,132
help me.

41
00:06:42,008 --> 00:06:44,510
Loki! Help!

42
00:06:50,850 --> 00:06:52,769
Shadows

43
00:06:53,061 --> 00:06:55,772
in the dark are crawling.

44
00:06:56,481 --> 00:07:00,525
Keeping watch and barring your way.

45
00:07:00,526 --> 00:07:04,072
As if the line could not be crossed.

46
00:07:05,031 --> 00:07:08,617
To every scream and every tremor.

47
00:07:08,618 --> 00:07:11,787
These walls remain the only witness.

48
00:07:11,788 --> 00:07:14,748
Every noise is etched in here.

49
00:07:14,749 --> 00:07:19,253
Like fire and ammunition for your memory.

50
00:07:20,630 --> 00:07:22,757
Heed the warnings.

51
00:07:24,008 --> 00:07:26,386
The threats poised to strike.

52
00:07:27,470 --> 00:07:31,140
For this world

53
00:07:31,808 --> 00:07:34,434
is not what you imagined.

54
00:07:34,435 --> 00:07:36,896
Heed the warnings.

55
00:07:37,897 --> 00:07:40,024
Open up your eyes.

56
00:07:41,317 --> 00:07:44,862
For this world

57
00:07:45,571 --> 00:07:48,115
is not what you imagined.

58
00:07:48,116 --> 00:07:52,954
Heed the warnings.

59
00:08:03,464 --> 00:08:05,007
So you’re awake, Lorelei.

60
00:08:05,675 --> 00:08:06,592
Perfect timing.

61
00:08:06,593 --> 00:08:11,806
You want to know what happened
to those missing students, right?

62
00:08:12,723 --> 00:08:14,142
I’ll let you know.

63
00:08:14,809 --> 00:08:18,187
First, I killed them one by one.

64
00:08:19,564 --> 00:08:22,275
One by one.

65
00:08:24,819 --> 00:08:26,571
Then I melted them.

66
00:08:28,322 --> 00:08:30,116
You know, I melted them, right?

67
00:08:33,286 --> 00:08:34,996
But since you’re special…

68
00:08:39,459 --> 00:08:41,502
I’ll melt you alive.

69
00:08:49,385 --> 00:08:51,220
Hey, can you see this?

70
00:08:55,516 --> 00:08:58,603
What? This is it. Are you ready, huh?

71
00:08:59,770 --> 00:09:01,397
Are you ready?

72
00:09:02,482 --> 00:09:04,066
This is it.

73
00:09:06,235 --> 00:09:07,612
Such a bother.

74
00:09:08,404 --> 00:09:09,906
Where were we?

75
00:09:10,948 --> 00:09:12,408
This is it.

76
00:09:14,785 --> 00:09:16,037
Shit!

77
00:09:18,706 --> 00:09:21,584
Don’t cause trouble, okay?
I’ll come back for you.

78
00:09:22,210 --> 00:09:25,630
I'm just going to answer this, okay?

79
00:09:31,052 --> 00:09:33,053
Don't make a sound! Come on!

80
00:09:33,054 --> 00:09:34,179
Don't make a sound!

81
00:09:34,180 --> 00:09:37,015
Don't! Don't! Don't!

82
00:09:37,016 --> 00:09:38,767
Don't make a sound! Don't make a sound!

83
00:09:38,768 --> 00:09:40,769
Please! Please! Please!
Don't make a sound!

84
00:09:40,770 --> 00:09:43,730
Don't make a sound!
Shut up! Shut up! I'll kill you!

85
00:09:43,731 --> 00:09:46,776
I'll kill you! Shut up! Damn it!

86
00:09:57,036 --> 00:09:58,328
- Mom.
- Hello?

87
00:09:58,329 --> 00:10:02,123
- Yes, Mom? Sorry, I missed your call. Mom.
- What are you doing? I’ve been calling.

88
00:10:02,124 --> 00:10:04,167
- Mom? Hello?
- You’re not answering your phone.

89
00:10:04,168 --> 00:10:06,962
Sorry, I was in class,
so I missed your call.

90
00:10:06,963 --> 00:10:08,756
Are you going home this sembreak?

91
00:10:09,423 --> 00:10:13,552
Your dad and aunt are asking me
if you’re still alive.

92
00:10:13,553 --> 00:10:15,221
What's going on with you?

93
00:10:15,930 --> 00:10:20,225
- Just tell Auntie and Dad I can’t go home.
- Where are you, really?

94
00:10:20,226 --> 00:10:22,728
- Sorry, Mom. Hello?
- Why won't you tell me?

95
00:10:23,229 --> 00:10:25,855
- Alright. Alright, Mom.
- What's that?

96
00:10:25,856 --> 00:10:27,524
- Help!
- Why so loud? Where are you? Son!

97
00:10:27,525 --> 00:10:28,734
Son!

98
00:10:29,151 --> 00:10:30,986
You... been at it for a while, huh?

99
00:10:30,987 --> 00:10:35,490
Since earlier! Since earlier!

100
00:10:35,491 --> 00:10:39,495
What's your problem?
I was talking to my mom!

101
00:10:40,079 --> 00:10:44,166
Shut up! You're so loud! You're so loud!

102
00:10:45,293 --> 00:10:46,973
You’ve really been at it for a while, huh!

103
00:10:49,630 --> 00:10:51,882
You’ve been at it since earlier.
You’re so annoying.

104
00:10:52,717 --> 00:10:54,343
What, huh?

105
00:10:55,261 --> 00:10:57,178
You really want to die?

106
00:10:57,179 --> 00:10:59,181
You're so annoying.

107
00:11:01,559 --> 00:11:02,768
Come here.

108
00:11:04,687 --> 00:11:07,857
- No. No.
- Don't cause trouble. Don't cause trouble!

109
00:11:23,831 --> 00:11:26,250
I admire your survival instincts,
for a woman.

110
00:11:26,667 --> 00:11:29,045
You’re so tiring! You’re so tiring!

111
00:11:35,176 --> 00:11:39,347
Sorry, I need to put you back there.

112
00:11:40,931 --> 00:11:42,850
I’m going to kill you!

113
00:11:48,022 --> 00:11:49,357
No! Please!

114
00:11:50,691 --> 00:11:52,735
No! No!

115
00:11:53,861 --> 00:11:54,987
Please.

116
00:11:57,907 --> 00:11:59,325
No!

117
00:12:20,429 --> 00:12:22,682
Lorelei! Lorelei! Are you okay?

118
00:12:23,557 --> 00:12:24,600
Lorelei.

119
00:12:26,185 --> 00:12:27,478
Lorelei.

120
00:12:32,858 --> 00:12:35,111
Lorelei, are you okay?

121
00:13:54,023 --> 00:13:55,274
Loki.

122
00:14:05,242 --> 00:14:06,494
Loki!

123
00:14:30,434 --> 00:14:32,478
I've been waiting so long for this, M.

124
00:14:33,646 --> 00:14:35,481
- How did you know...
- Quite clever...

125
00:14:36,065 --> 00:14:37,358
I must say.

126
00:14:38,484 --> 00:14:41,110
The way you managed
to kidnap those victims

127
00:14:41,111 --> 00:14:44,782
without anyone noticing
and alerting the campus police.

128
00:14:46,534 --> 00:14:48,536
How you handled those corpses,

129
00:14:49,119 --> 00:14:52,832
letting the victim’s body melt
inside the drum.

130
00:15:05,845 --> 00:15:08,848
But it was very foolish how you disposed

131
00:15:09,431 --> 00:15:11,183
the liquefied remains.

132
00:15:14,061 --> 00:15:15,354
Just so you know,

133
00:15:15,938 --> 00:15:19,567
sodium hydroxide
creates a malodorous smell

134
00:15:20,317 --> 00:15:21,860
when it melts a human body.

135
00:15:21,861 --> 00:15:24,487
On the basement, by the anatomy room,

136
00:15:24,488 --> 00:15:26,323
there’s always a foul smell.

137
00:15:26,740 --> 00:15:29,159
Sometimes, I feel like
there’s someone there.

138
00:15:29,660 --> 00:15:32,203
Does it smell like something’s rotting?

139
00:15:32,204 --> 00:15:33,538
No,

140
00:15:33,539 --> 00:15:34,957
it’s like chemical.

141
00:15:35,416 --> 00:15:37,417
It hurts my nose.

142
00:15:37,418 --> 00:15:39,503
It’s giving me headache too.

143
00:15:42,631 --> 00:15:44,008
Where’s Lori?

144
00:15:59,064 --> 00:16:00,940
Where’s that foul smell coming from?

145
00:16:00,941 --> 00:16:02,693
It’s near the anatomy room.

146
00:16:05,487 --> 00:16:06,530
In the anatomy...

147
00:16:08,949 --> 00:16:11,702
Blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

148
00:16:14,413 --> 00:16:16,498
You know a lot!

149
00:16:17,333 --> 00:16:20,210
Come, let me give you
a refresher in chemistry.

150
00:16:25,966 --> 00:16:27,426
Harder!

151
00:16:30,596 --> 00:16:31,889
I must say…

152
00:16:34,975 --> 00:16:36,644
I’m a little disappointed in you.

153
00:16:38,604 --> 00:16:42,566
I thought you’d be smarter
than the other criminals I’ve encountered.

154
00:16:59,166 --> 00:17:00,626
Now, I have a question.

155
00:17:01,335 --> 00:17:04,004
Are you regretting killing Rhea now?

156
00:17:05,214 --> 00:17:06,548
Are you crazy?

157
00:17:08,467 --> 00:17:11,387
Who are you talking about? Who’s Rhea?

158
00:17:13,555 --> 00:17:15,474
You actually managed to laugh, huh!

159
00:17:16,100 --> 00:17:18,435
Okay. Let’s do this the old way.

160
00:17:20,020 --> 00:17:21,521
An eye for an eye,

161
00:17:21,522 --> 00:17:23,023
and a tooth for a tooth.

162
00:17:30,489 --> 00:17:33,283
You killed those other girls
by melting their bodies.

163
00:17:35,661 --> 00:17:37,538
I’ll do the same to you.

164
00:17:38,455 --> 00:17:40,039
Wait, you’re wrong.

165
00:17:40,040 --> 00:17:42,793
Who? M? I’m not M!

166
00:17:43,419 --> 00:17:44,670
Who’s M?

167
00:17:45,129 --> 00:17:46,546
Now you’re denying it.

168
00:17:46,547 --> 00:17:48,214
I’m really not M!

169
00:17:48,215 --> 00:17:50,384
If you hadn’t poisoned Genesis,

170
00:17:51,218 --> 00:17:53,637
he definitely reported that you’re M.

171
00:17:53,721 --> 00:17:55,472
I can’t do that!

172
00:17:55,556 --> 00:17:57,891
Believe me, I didn’t kill him.

173
00:18:06,984 --> 00:18:08,944
I’m really not M!

174
00:18:09,611 --> 00:18:10,904
He knows you.

175
00:18:12,531 --> 00:18:15,992
So you kept him quiet
while the cops escorted him,

176
00:18:15,993 --> 00:18:19,288
by using a succinylcholine syringe, right?

177
00:18:20,122 --> 00:18:21,664
Right.

178
00:18:21,665 --> 00:18:23,083
So you admit it?

179
00:18:24,001 --> 00:18:25,127
You are M.

180
00:18:25,794 --> 00:18:28,671
The M behind all these killings!

181
00:18:28,672 --> 00:18:30,466
The M who killed Rhea!

182
00:18:30,924 --> 00:18:33,051
Yes, okay?

183
00:18:33,052 --> 00:18:37,931
Yes, I'm the one who killed Genesis
and those three women.

184
00:18:40,309 --> 00:18:41,477
But…

185
00:18:44,146 --> 00:18:46,230
I don’t even know that Rhea!

186
00:18:46,231 --> 00:18:48,317
And I’m not M!

187
00:18:48,567 --> 00:18:50,152
I’m not M!

188
00:18:50,694 --> 00:18:53,030
Liar. Don’t play with me!

189
00:18:53,572 --> 00:18:56,324
I’m not M. I’m not M.

190
00:18:56,325 --> 00:18:57,742
- I'm not lying.
- Enough!

191
00:18:57,743 --> 00:18:59,536
- I’m not lying!
- Enough!

192
00:19:01,830 --> 00:19:05,334
Why should I believe you,
when everything you say is a lie!

193
00:19:09,254 --> 00:19:11,172
This is for Mylene,

194
00:19:11,173 --> 00:19:12,465
Michelle,

195
00:19:12,466 --> 00:19:13,592
Madonna

196
00:19:14,176 --> 00:19:15,511
and for Rhea.

197
00:19:16,261 --> 00:19:17,554
See you in hell.

198
00:19:18,722 --> 00:19:20,431
No. Loki, that’s enough!

199
00:19:20,432 --> 00:19:22,392
- Let me go! Let me go!
- That’s enough!

200
00:19:22,476 --> 00:19:23,559
No.

201
00:19:23,560 --> 00:19:25,686
Do you really think
what you’re doing is right?

202
00:19:25,687 --> 00:19:26,980
What the hell do I care?

203
00:19:27,481 --> 00:19:29,650
This is on me.
You don’t need to care about it!

204
00:19:31,610 --> 00:19:32,778
Loki…

205
00:19:33,445 --> 00:19:35,030
if you do that,

206
00:19:35,989 --> 00:19:38,283
you’re no different from him.

207
00:19:39,493 --> 00:19:42,496
You’re turning to a murderer
just like him!

208
00:19:44,832 --> 00:19:46,040
Besides,

209
00:19:46,041 --> 00:19:48,793
we don’t have proof
beyond reasonable doubt

210
00:19:48,794 --> 00:19:50,796
that he's the one who killed Rhea.

211
00:19:52,589 --> 00:19:53,799
Loki…

212
00:19:54,299 --> 00:19:56,385
how do you think Rhea would feel

213
00:19:56,885 --> 00:19:59,054
knowing you became the monster

214
00:19:59,388 --> 00:20:00,931
that you once fought?

215
00:20:02,975 --> 00:20:08,939
Do you think Rhea would want to know
you killed that person

216
00:20:09,189 --> 00:20:10,482
for her?

217
00:20:12,401 --> 00:20:13,569
Loki…

218
00:20:15,654 --> 00:20:16,738
Loki…

219
00:20:17,573 --> 00:20:19,032
this isn’t you.

220
00:20:20,284 --> 00:20:21,493
Please…

221
00:20:22,870 --> 00:20:24,496
think about this.

222
00:20:33,839 --> 00:20:35,007
You’re right.

223
00:20:38,260 --> 00:20:39,720
I’m not like him.

224
00:20:41,889 --> 00:20:43,515
I don’t wanna be like him.

225
00:21:01,491 --> 00:21:05,494
Your wrist only has minor abrasions
from being tied up.

226
00:21:05,495 --> 00:21:07,956
But other than that,
you have no other injuries.

227
00:21:10,083 --> 00:21:11,460
Are you okay?

228
00:21:11,919 --> 00:21:13,629
Do you feel anything?

229
00:21:15,130 --> 00:21:17,090
Nothing hurts on my body…

230
00:21:18,717 --> 00:21:20,385
I’m not okay.

231
00:21:21,053 --> 00:21:25,682
Here in the infirmary,
we treat physical injuries.

232
00:21:25,724 --> 00:21:28,059
But when you go
through that kind of violence,

233
00:21:28,060 --> 00:21:29,852
like what happened to you,

234
00:21:29,853 --> 00:21:32,689
there’s mental and psychological damage.

235
00:21:33,398 --> 00:21:34,524
Wait.

236
00:21:36,985 --> 00:21:40,989
Just go to her office or give her a call,
she can help.

237
00:21:41,865 --> 00:21:43,824
Thank you, Nurse?

238
00:21:43,825 --> 00:21:46,536
Melissa. Mel, for short.

239
00:21:47,537 --> 00:21:50,706
Tip for you,
when the bad memories come back,

240
00:21:50,707 --> 00:21:52,709
take a deep breath in through your nose...

241
00:21:53,460 --> 00:21:55,587
and slowly out through your mouth.

242
00:21:58,590 --> 00:21:59,800
See?

243
00:22:01,176 --> 00:22:02,301
Nice.

244
00:22:02,302 --> 00:22:04,136
I sometimes think

245
00:22:04,137 --> 00:22:07,556
that since students’ mental health
isn’t being taken care of,

246
00:22:07,557 --> 00:22:10,768
the killings on campus keep happening.

247
00:22:10,769 --> 00:22:13,939
It’s sad, they’re so young.

248
00:22:14,815 --> 00:22:17,943
Has it been like this
at Clark U for a long time?

249
00:22:17,985 --> 00:22:22,113
Honestly, it’s normal for students here
to suddenly travel

250
00:22:22,114 --> 00:22:24,825
or drop out mid-semester.

251
00:22:25,284 --> 00:22:27,077
But since last year,

252
00:22:27,619 --> 00:22:30,914
it’s been happening more often
and it’s not normal anymore.

253
00:22:31,540 --> 00:22:36,461
It’s possible they just dropped out,
or fell victim to a crime.

254
00:22:37,170 --> 00:22:41,882
I just don’t understand why the admin
doesn’t seem to be doing anything.

255
00:22:41,883 --> 00:22:47,097
Some parents are pulling their kids out
because of what’s happening.

256
00:22:47,889 --> 00:22:50,100
Okay, I’ll let you be for now.

257
00:22:54,521 --> 00:22:55,521
How are you?

258
00:22:57,480 --> 00:22:58,981
How's your fist?

259
00:22:59,187 --> 00:23:01,356
It's nothing. Just a bit red.

260
00:23:03,125 --> 00:23:04,126
Come here.

261
00:23:13,832 --> 00:23:17,169
Maybe Nurse Mel is right.

262
00:23:17,669 --> 00:23:22,841
The students' mental health
gets neglected, so this is what happens.

263
00:23:24,634 --> 00:23:26,845
We can’t blame it all on mental health.

264
00:23:28,138 --> 00:23:29,514
Sometimes,

265
00:23:30,307 --> 00:23:33,268
people are just pure evil.

266
00:23:38,940 --> 00:23:40,317
Chief Estrada…

267
00:23:40,817 --> 00:23:42,402
you have something for us?

268
00:23:42,611 --> 00:23:45,989
Did John Bautista admit he's M?

269
00:23:46,740 --> 00:23:49,117
No, he didn't. But...

270
00:23:49,451 --> 00:23:53,830
this is the last part of John's confession
that I think will lead us to M.

271
00:23:54,164 --> 00:23:57,084
Watch this video of his interrogation.

272
00:24:00,212 --> 00:24:03,173
Why won't you believe me, huh?

273
00:24:03,757 --> 00:24:05,759
I really don't know him!

274
00:24:06,259 --> 00:24:08,011
I really don't know him!

275
00:24:08,178 --> 00:24:10,430
I only talked to him on the phone!

276
00:24:10,847 --> 00:24:14,101
Only on the phone.
I haven't even seen him!

277
00:24:14,518 --> 00:24:17,311
Sometimes he sends people

278
00:24:17,312 --> 00:24:19,314
but that's it.

279
00:24:20,273 --> 00:24:23,652
I haven’t even seen him. Believe me!

280
00:24:23,944 --> 00:24:27,072
Can you describe his voice?

281
00:24:28,865 --> 00:24:30,158
Just…

282
00:24:30,784 --> 00:24:33,286
cold and deep.

283
00:24:34,788 --> 00:24:38,208
The kind that gives you
chills when you hear it.

284
00:24:40,252 --> 00:24:45,757
Hasn’t any of his people
mentioned his name?

285
00:24:46,341 --> 00:24:49,552
None at all!
I’ve been telling you this, haven’t I?

286
00:24:49,553 --> 00:24:50,846
None.

287
00:24:51,138 --> 00:24:53,390
I only know him as M.

288
00:24:53,723 --> 00:24:54,891
That's it.

289
00:24:55,350 --> 00:24:56,435
But…

290
00:24:57,144 --> 00:24:58,854
But he has people.

291
00:24:59,229 --> 00:25:00,564
He has people.

292
00:25:00,981 --> 00:25:02,732
He’s called by another name.

293
00:25:04,776 --> 00:25:06,027
What was it again…

294
00:25:09,072 --> 00:25:10,240
John?

295
00:25:11,491 --> 00:25:13,660
John? John!

296
00:25:14,453 --> 00:25:16,413
Call an ambulance!

297
00:25:20,041 --> 00:25:24,337
Chief, I heard John say in the video
that he was talking to someone.

298
00:25:24,629 --> 00:25:27,131
I can verify that information to be true,

299
00:25:27,132 --> 00:25:28,967
because while I was in the drum,

300
00:25:29,092 --> 00:25:33,221
I heard him talking to someone
on the phone.

301
00:25:34,139 --> 00:25:37,142
He was talking to someone before his mom.

302
00:25:40,562 --> 00:25:41,980
He called someone?

303
00:25:42,355 --> 00:25:45,775
Chief, didn’t you get John’s phone?

304
00:25:46,026 --> 00:25:48,904
To trace
who he was last talking to earlier.

305
00:25:49,029 --> 00:25:51,489
We got his phone,
but it’s already damaged.

306
00:25:51,490 --> 00:25:56,119
Chemicals spilled on it. It's corroded,
so we can't use it as evidence.

307
00:26:07,297 --> 00:26:08,590
Loki.

308
00:26:11,009 --> 00:26:13,178
He’s everywhere, Lorelei.

309
00:26:13,386 --> 00:26:17,807
He’s got eyes and ears everywhere.

310
00:26:21,520 --> 00:26:22,646
Wait…

311
00:26:26,358 --> 00:26:29,986
John's mouth is still moving
in the video.

312
00:26:30,654 --> 00:26:32,656
Looks like he’s trying to say something.

313
00:26:39,412 --> 00:26:41,581
Moria... Moriarty.

314
00:26:44,167 --> 00:26:45,627
Moriarty?

315
00:27:19,619 --> 00:27:21,454
Moriarty!

316
00:27:22,205 --> 00:27:23,707
Moria...

317
00:27:24,165 --> 00:27:26,251
Moriarty!

318
00:27:26,835 --> 00:27:28,419
Moria...

319
00:27:28,420 --> 00:27:30,170
Moria...

320
00:27:30,171 --> 00:27:32,340
Moriarty.

321
00:27:32,799 --> 00:27:37,220
Moria... Moriarty!

322
00:27:37,679 --> 00:27:39,722
Moria...

323
00:27:39,723 --> 00:27:42,142
Moriarty.

324
00:27:42,475 --> 00:27:44,351
Moria.

325
00:27:44,352 --> 00:27:46,895
Moriarty.

326
00:27:46,896 --> 00:27:48,690
Moria.

327
00:27:49,065 --> 00:27:51,026
Moria.

328
00:27:51,735 --> 00:27:53,278
Moria.

329
00:27:53,445 --> 00:27:55,822
Moriarty.

330
00:27:56,072 --> 00:27:57,907
Moria.

331
00:27:58,283 --> 00:28:00,451
Moriarty.

332
00:28:00,452 --> 00:28:01,828
Moria.

333
00:28:02,162 --> 00:28:04,080
Moriarty.

334
00:28:04,623 --> 00:28:06,540
Moria.

335
00:28:06,541 --> 00:28:09,711
Moriarty.

336
00:28:20,930 --> 00:28:22,223
Moriarty.

337
00:28:24,100 --> 00:28:25,352
Moriarty.

338
00:28:27,520 --> 00:28:28,688
Moriarty.

339
00:28:30,815 --> 00:28:32,150
Moriarty.

340
00:28:34,152 --> 00:28:35,362
Moriarty.

341
00:28:37,447 --> 00:28:38,698
Moriarty.

342
00:28:40,784 --> 00:28:42,035
Moriarty.

343
00:28:44,287 --> 00:28:46,164
I heard a scream in your room.

344
00:28:46,873 --> 00:28:48,792
I thought you were having nightmares.

345
00:28:49,876 --> 00:28:50,960
Don’t worry.

346
00:28:51,544 --> 00:28:55,674
It’s normal, especially for those
who’ve gone through near-death experience.

347
00:28:56,591 --> 00:28:57,884
Yeah, right.

348
00:29:00,512 --> 00:29:03,890
I’m having nightmares from you
replaying John’s video over and over.

349
00:29:04,474 --> 00:29:06,893
I thought you were doing
some kind of ritual.

350
00:29:11,439 --> 00:29:13,858
Have you ever actually slept?

351
00:29:15,318 --> 00:29:16,903
Don’t tell me…

352
00:29:17,612 --> 00:29:19,406
you worked on this all night.

353
00:29:21,741 --> 00:29:22,951
Do you know them?

354
00:29:28,206 --> 00:29:29,666
I don’t think so.

355
00:29:29,749 --> 00:29:31,292
But, wait…

356
00:29:31,960 --> 00:29:34,170
that guy looks familiar.

357
00:29:34,838 --> 00:29:38,591
I feel like I’ve watched him
in a series before.

358
00:29:39,092 --> 00:29:40,635
Why do you ask?

359
00:29:42,095 --> 00:29:44,012
They're actors who played Moriarty

360
00:29:44,013 --> 00:29:47,307
in the modern adaptations
of Sherlock Holmes.

361
00:29:47,308 --> 00:29:49,144
And James Moriarty

362
00:29:49,769 --> 00:29:52,981
is considered as the arch-nemesis
of Sherlock.

363
00:29:54,315 --> 00:29:57,694
Moriarty is a professor of Mathematics,

364
00:29:58,945 --> 00:30:01,322
known as "the Napoleon of crime.”

365
00:30:02,073 --> 00:30:06,661
The mastermind
behind half of the evil in the world.

366
00:30:09,664 --> 00:30:11,666
So you’re saying…

367
00:30:12,167 --> 00:30:16,295
Moriarty is just the codename
of the person you’re after?

368
00:30:16,296 --> 00:30:17,630
Exactly.

369
00:30:18,590 --> 00:30:22,969
How dare he use
the name of my most favorite

370
00:30:23,428 --> 00:30:24,846
antagonist.

371
00:30:26,806 --> 00:30:28,683
But why is he killing?

372
00:30:29,476 --> 00:30:31,644
What wrong did they do to him?

373
00:30:32,687 --> 00:30:36,608
The victims didn't do anything
to make Moriarty want to kill them.

374
00:30:38,276 --> 00:30:39,944
Well, except for Janine.

375
00:30:40,820 --> 00:30:43,031
Her case is separate from Moriarty’s.

376
00:30:43,490 --> 00:30:46,993
And it’s clear that Janine’s case
is a crime of passion.

377
00:30:47,577 --> 00:30:49,245
But for the rest…

378
00:30:50,079 --> 00:30:51,664
they’re all connected.

379
00:30:53,041 --> 00:30:55,585
Perhaps, Moriarty...

380
00:30:56,711 --> 00:30:58,254
like in the novel,

381
00:30:59,547 --> 00:31:01,382
this is playing wilth Holmes,

382
00:31:02,801 --> 00:31:05,136
and I am his Holmes.

383
00:31:06,846 --> 00:31:07,972
Wait.

384
00:31:09,641 --> 00:31:11,351
Like what I’ve said before,

385
00:31:11,893 --> 00:31:13,394
sometimes,

386
00:31:13,853 --> 00:31:16,606
people are just pure evil.

387
00:31:18,233 --> 00:31:19,943
I just remembered…

388
00:31:21,110 --> 00:31:22,820
someone called John

389
00:31:22,821 --> 00:31:24,405
while I was in the drum.

390
00:31:25,782 --> 00:31:27,784
Though, it’s kind of baffling, but…

391
00:31:28,284 --> 00:31:33,248
I heard him tell the other person
they’ll teach you a lesson.

392
00:31:35,834 --> 00:31:38,878
You think he was speaking
to Moriarty at that time?

393
00:31:39,879 --> 00:31:41,256
I wasn’t there.

394
00:31:42,006 --> 00:31:43,424
I can’t say.

395
00:31:45,218 --> 00:31:46,678
But it's possible.

396
00:31:48,471 --> 00:31:51,057
Since, Moriarty ordered all of that.

397
00:31:52,058 --> 00:31:54,561
And I just feel strange about this case.

398
00:31:55,687 --> 00:31:57,021
Strange?

399
00:31:58,273 --> 00:31:59,274
Yeah.

400
00:32:01,359 --> 00:32:06,030
Now we know
someone’s working for Moriarty.

401
00:32:07,657 --> 00:32:11,494
It’s possible
someone’s inside the campus police.

402
00:32:12,704 --> 00:32:15,081
And that explains
why the phone was destroyed.

403
00:32:15,582 --> 00:32:18,501
And that explains why John was poisoned

404
00:32:18,835 --> 00:32:20,753
while in police custody.

405
00:32:26,384 --> 00:32:30,096
Alright, I’m going back to sleep.

406
00:32:30,972 --> 00:32:32,015
Good night.

407
00:32:32,432 --> 00:32:33,892
By the way, Lorelei.

408
00:32:37,604 --> 00:32:39,147
I have a request,

409
00:32:39,647 --> 00:32:43,109
I just want you to keep an eye
out of anything suspicious.

410
00:32:43,484 --> 00:32:44,986
And stay vigilant.

411
00:32:45,987 --> 00:32:47,697
Especially when you’re alone.

412
00:32:48,948 --> 00:32:50,825
I hope this doesn’t happen to you again.

413
00:33:48,675 --> 00:33:51,218
It’s sad to think that all we can do
for those who passed

414
00:33:51,219 --> 00:33:52,762
is to remember them

415
00:33:53,471 --> 00:33:55,473
and fight for their justice.

416
00:33:57,767 --> 00:33:59,560
But they won’t remember it anymore,

417
00:34:00,103 --> 00:34:01,521
because they’re gone.

418
00:34:03,231 --> 00:34:05,483
This isn’t for those who are gone.

419
00:34:06,651 --> 00:34:08,361
This is for those left behind.

420
00:34:10,279 --> 00:34:14,075
Maybe this was the only way
they could think of,

421
00:34:14,701 --> 00:34:17,036
to show their love
for their dead loved ones.

422
00:34:52,447 --> 00:34:55,450
Why are all your exam scores zero?

423
00:34:56,117 --> 00:34:58,786
Are you disappointed
because I got so many zeros on the exam?

424
00:34:59,746 --> 00:35:01,622
I’m not disappointed.

425
00:35:02,081 --> 00:35:04,792
I just can’t believe
that you’ve got zeroes.

426
00:35:05,126 --> 00:35:07,627
I mean, with how smart you are,

427
00:35:07,628 --> 00:35:09,714
you didn’t answer a single one?

428
00:35:10,923 --> 00:35:12,425
Honestly,

429
00:35:12,759 --> 00:35:16,596
I’m not like everyone else
who’s obsessed with grades and awards.

430
00:35:18,181 --> 00:35:20,516
I refuse to be enslaved by numbers.

431
00:35:23,186 --> 00:35:25,605
Those medals and certificates

432
00:35:26,272 --> 00:35:27,857
don’t mean anything to me.

433
00:35:28,232 --> 00:35:30,735
Aren’t you worried you might fail?

434
00:35:31,152 --> 00:35:33,278
Enrolling again would cost so much.

435
00:35:33,279 --> 00:35:35,573
And on top of that,
you’ll be delayed graduating.

436
00:35:38,409 --> 00:35:39,535
Right now…

437
00:35:40,078 --> 00:35:41,871
that’s the least of my priorities.

438
00:35:42,955 --> 00:35:44,457
What matters to me

439
00:35:45,249 --> 00:35:46,501
is this club.

440
00:35:48,586 --> 00:35:53,466
I know you have responsibilities
in this club and to our fellow students.

441
00:35:53,716 --> 00:35:55,342
But let me remind you, Loki,

442
00:35:55,343 --> 00:35:58,345
at the end of the day,
we’re still students.

443
00:35:58,346 --> 00:36:01,390
And our top priority is still to graduate.

444
00:36:01,891 --> 00:36:06,312
We need to be equipped
with the proper skills and knowledge,

445
00:36:06,771 --> 00:36:09,315
for anything we choose to do
in the real world.

446
00:36:14,487 --> 00:36:16,155
Fine, whatever.

447
00:36:19,617 --> 00:36:21,910
Sorry to bother you, can I come in?

448
00:36:21,911 --> 00:36:23,453
Yes. Of course. Come in.

449
00:36:23,454 --> 00:36:24,956
- Okay, have a seat.
- Wow.

450
00:36:25,164 --> 00:36:27,333
Your room is really nice.

451
00:36:27,750 --> 00:36:30,253
You dropped by, what’s up?

452
00:36:32,797 --> 00:36:34,882
I’d like to get your opinion.

453
00:36:35,091 --> 00:36:37,635
I’m speaking on behalf
of the Paranormal Club.

454
00:36:39,178 --> 00:36:42,264
We have a ghost hunting activity

455
00:36:42,265 --> 00:36:44,516
at the abandoned school building.

456
00:36:44,517 --> 00:36:46,101
We’ve been going back and forth
for five days,

457
00:36:46,102 --> 00:36:47,979
but still haven’t seen anything.

458
00:36:49,564 --> 00:36:50,940
But this last time…

459
00:36:51,357 --> 00:36:52,524
we caught something.

460
00:36:52,525 --> 00:36:54,901
Here. Watch this, watch this. Here.

461
00:36:54,902 --> 00:36:57,196
- Loki! Come on, let’s watch.
- Here, here.

462
00:36:57,488 --> 00:36:59,615
Wait. Here.

463
00:37:02,702 --> 00:37:04,828
Guys, we’re on the 2nd floor.

464
00:37:04,829 --> 00:37:08,124
So far, we haven’t seen any ghosts.

465
00:37:08,374 --> 00:37:10,168
Looks like there’s really nothing.

466
00:37:10,543 --> 00:37:14,589
Seems like the person who told us
was spreading fake news.

467
00:37:15,047 --> 00:37:17,175
- What a waste of time.
- Yeah, right.

468
00:37:20,428 --> 00:37:22,597
Shit, did you hear that?

469
00:37:23,639 --> 00:37:25,640
Right? Did you hear that?

470
00:37:25,641 --> 00:37:27,225
- Did you hear that?
- Hey.

471
00:37:27,226 --> 00:37:28,561
Hey.

472
00:37:29,187 --> 00:37:30,645
Yeah!

473
00:37:30,646 --> 00:37:32,939
- It's not a good joke!
- No, it's true!

474
00:37:32,940 --> 00:37:36,611
- Hey! Don’t mess with us!
- Stay quiet!

475
00:37:37,987 --> 00:37:40,948
Guys, this might be real,
there’s a ghost here.

476
00:37:42,241 --> 00:37:44,034
Oh, there!

477
00:37:44,035 --> 00:37:46,370
Listen, there’s something.

478
00:37:47,038 --> 00:37:49,831
Hey, shit. Andrew peed himself!

479
00:37:49,832 --> 00:37:51,791
- Did you pee yourself?
- No way! No way!

480
00:37:51,792 --> 00:37:53,376
- Andrew, you peed.
- You're gross. You're gross.

481
00:37:53,377 --> 00:37:55,378
- No, it just got wet.
- You're gross. You're gross.

482
00:37:55,379 --> 00:37:58,049
I told you!
There. Did you hear that?

483
00:37:58,716 --> 00:38:00,718
So clear. Did you hear that?

484
00:38:02,178 --> 00:38:03,429
Right?

485
00:38:04,639 --> 00:38:06,098
Right?

486
00:38:09,810 --> 00:38:12,688
Since when do we even solve
paranormal stuff?

487
00:38:13,731 --> 00:38:16,900
Come on, Loki.
Rosetta’s asking for our help.

488
00:38:16,901 --> 00:38:20,905
But paranormal cases
are the turf of the Paranormal Club.

489
00:38:22,448 --> 00:38:25,742
They’re the ones who should investigate
supernatural phenomena,

490
00:38:25,743 --> 00:38:27,453
whether it’s real or not.

491
00:38:27,954 --> 00:38:33,708
We at the Q.E.D. Club
rely solely on facts and evidences.

492
00:38:33,709 --> 00:38:35,002
Loki!

493
00:38:35,419 --> 00:38:37,672
What? I’m stating facts.

494
00:38:38,005 --> 00:38:40,299
Do you give your word, Loki?

495
00:38:41,259 --> 00:38:43,678
And that question is relevant because?

496
00:38:44,720 --> 00:38:47,681
You told me when we met
at the White Hostel

497
00:38:47,682 --> 00:38:50,434
that you’d do me a big favor…

498
00:38:50,810 --> 00:38:54,897
if I post your photos on CU Confessions
while you’re investigating.

499
00:38:55,189 --> 00:38:56,940
I even promoted Lori’s blog

500
00:38:56,941 --> 00:38:59,610
so more people can read
about your solved cases.

501
00:38:59,986 --> 00:39:02,405
I don’t usually owe a favor to anyone.

502
00:39:03,155 --> 00:39:06,617
But we may owe you one,
if you do exactly what you’ve said.

503
00:39:06,951 --> 00:39:08,493
Any kind of help

504
00:39:08,494 --> 00:39:10,870
would be a big deal
to get our club noticed.

505
00:39:10,871 --> 00:39:12,164
Sure!

506
00:39:12,373 --> 00:39:14,125
My pleasure!

507
00:39:15,293 --> 00:39:19,422
I’ll call it quits if you help us
figure out that mysterious sound.

508
00:39:19,797 --> 00:39:21,715
Yes, Rosseta, good thing,

509
00:39:21,716 --> 00:39:25,802
Loki here is such an honorable man,
and he honors his every word.

510
00:39:25,803 --> 00:39:28,054
So you can count on us to help.

511
00:39:28,055 --> 00:39:29,180
Yay! Okay.

512
00:39:29,181 --> 00:39:31,474
So see you
at the abandoned school building, okay?

513
00:39:31,475 --> 00:39:33,060
I’ll just send you the address.

514
00:39:33,602 --> 00:39:35,146
Don’t ghost us, okay?

515
00:39:38,316 --> 00:39:41,986
Nothing. Bye. Thank you.

516
00:39:46,073 --> 00:39:50,494
I wish someone would walk in and ask us
to solve a far more engaging case.

517
00:39:55,624 --> 00:39:56,959
Professor Morayta!

518
00:39:57,626 --> 00:39:58,627
Lorelei.

519
00:39:59,253 --> 00:40:01,630
- Oh, you’re a member here?
- Yes.

520
00:40:01,839 --> 00:40:04,467
As a journ student,
you like solving problems.

521
00:40:05,384 --> 00:40:06,760
Did you just pass by?

522
00:40:06,761 --> 00:40:11,265
Yes, since your club is good
at solving problems, I came here.

523
00:40:11,307 --> 00:40:12,892
Oh, well. Thank you, sir.

524
00:40:13,017 --> 00:40:16,770
Oh, by the way, this is Loki Mendez,
our club president.

525
00:40:16,771 --> 00:40:21,317
Loki, this is Professor Morayta,
our Math 100 teacher.

526
00:40:21,650 --> 00:40:22,651
Loki?

527
00:40:22,902 --> 00:40:24,695
Like the Norse trickster god?

528
00:40:25,237 --> 00:40:26,322
Mm-hmm.

529
00:40:26,364 --> 00:40:29,658
I’ve heard so much about your club
and it’s a pleasure to finally meet you.

530
00:40:38,501 --> 00:40:41,295
So, Prof, did you witness a murder?

531
00:40:41,670 --> 00:40:43,506
Or find a decomposing corpse?

532
00:40:44,548 --> 00:40:45,716
Either way,

533
00:40:46,509 --> 00:40:48,052
we’re obliged to assist.

534
00:40:49,053 --> 00:40:53,057
At least it's way better
than chasing a nonexistent ghost.

535
00:40:53,265 --> 00:40:54,308
Right?

536
00:40:55,518 --> 00:40:57,198
I didn’t want to make a big deal
out of it,

537
00:40:57,770 --> 00:41:00,106
so I didn’t go to campus police.

538
00:41:00,648 --> 00:41:02,900
No one died or got hurt,

539
00:41:03,234 --> 00:41:04,235
thankfully.

540
00:41:04,819 --> 00:41:06,404
I have a student,

541
00:41:06,821 --> 00:41:10,032
Stein Alberts, 3rd year BS Math.

542
00:41:10,616 --> 00:41:14,537
Today’s our screening
to become Clark U’s representative.

543
00:41:14,870 --> 00:41:17,081
Master Math is next month.

544
00:41:17,665 --> 00:41:22,503
It’s an intercollegiate math competition
where Stein’s a topnotcher.

545
00:41:23,504 --> 00:41:25,005
Actually, he’s really good.

546
00:41:25,464 --> 00:41:26,590
But...

547
00:41:27,591 --> 00:41:30,177
he didn’t go to class.

548
00:41:30,803 --> 00:41:33,596
We tried calling and texting him,

549
00:41:33,597 --> 00:41:36,851
even on all his social media,
but nothing got a seen mark.

550
00:41:37,435 --> 00:41:39,019
When did anyone last see him?

551
00:41:39,311 --> 00:41:44,275
His classmates said they saw him
around 4 p.m. at the library,

552
00:41:44,608 --> 00:41:46,068
to do research.

553
00:41:46,527 --> 00:41:49,363
But that’s unlikely,
since Stein doesn’t need to review.

554
00:41:50,281 --> 00:41:53,159
Later that night,
he did not come home to his dorm.

555
00:41:53,367 --> 00:41:56,829
His dormmates said they thought
he slept over at a classmate’s place.

556
00:41:57,538 --> 00:42:01,000
Prof, if Stein didn’t make it
through the screening,

557
00:42:01,167 --> 00:42:03,544
who’s the 3rd year’s representative?

558
00:42:04,378 --> 00:42:05,795
Monica Segundo.

559
00:42:05,796 --> 00:42:07,548
She’s second in their block.

560
00:42:07,882 --> 00:42:09,841
But Stein always ends up on top.

561
00:42:09,842 --> 00:42:14,012
I know Monica has wanted to join
the math competition for a long time.

562
00:42:14,013 --> 00:42:15,473
But since Stein’s out,

563
00:42:15,806 --> 00:42:17,099
she’s next in line.

564
00:42:29,361 --> 00:42:30,863
Excuse me, ma’am.

565
00:42:31,030 --> 00:42:32,822
I just want to ask,

566
00:42:32,823 --> 00:42:37,077
did you see this man yesterday,
around 4 p.m.?

567
00:42:37,661 --> 00:42:42,124
Yes, I saw him. He even left his bag here.

568
00:42:42,374 --> 00:42:45,586
He was in a hurry. Maybe around 4:30?

569
00:42:46,337 --> 00:42:48,422
He just left his bag?

570
00:42:49,381 --> 00:42:53,010
This is his bag. You can return it to him.

571
00:42:53,928 --> 00:42:56,305
Okay. Thank you.

572
00:43:11,111 --> 00:43:12,571
Look what I’ve found.

573
00:43:13,113 --> 00:43:14,323
What is that?

574
00:43:14,907 --> 00:43:17,368
That rugged bag does not suit you.

575
00:43:17,409 --> 00:43:19,036
This is Stein’s bag.

576
00:43:19,078 --> 00:43:20,913
I asked around at the library.

577
00:43:21,497 --> 00:43:25,960
Didn’t Professor Morayta say
someone saw him there yesterday?

578
00:43:26,502 --> 00:43:31,674
Well, the librarian said he left this bag
and didn’t come back.

579
00:43:32,091 --> 00:43:36,262
So my guess is there might be a clue here
about his whereabouts.

580
00:43:37,012 --> 00:43:39,431
That’s her, Stein’s blockmate,

581
00:43:39,723 --> 00:43:41,433
or so-called rival.

582
00:43:42,518 --> 00:43:44,562
Hi! Excuse me.

583
00:43:45,271 --> 00:43:47,773
Are you Stein Alberts’ blockmate?

584
00:43:49,024 --> 00:43:50,192
That weirdo,

585
00:43:50,317 --> 00:43:51,860
he didn’t go to class today.

586
00:43:51,944 --> 00:43:52,903
He probably chickened out,

587
00:43:52,904 --> 00:43:55,281
so he decided not to show up
for the screening.

588
00:43:56,448 --> 00:43:58,408
You’re Monica Segundo,

589
00:43:58,409 --> 00:44:01,495
the eternal number two
of your class, right?

590
00:44:01,662 --> 00:44:04,039
Yeah. I don’t know you.

591
00:44:04,498 --> 00:44:06,250
Congratulations, by the way.

592
00:44:06,709 --> 00:44:09,335
You’ve been chosen
as your batch representative

593
00:44:09,336 --> 00:44:10,963
in math quiz bee.

594
00:44:11,213 --> 00:44:17,386
You’re lucky your toughest rival
didn’t show up on your screening day.

595
00:44:17,803 --> 00:44:19,638
What a coincidence.

596
00:44:20,264 --> 00:44:22,433
I have no idea what you’re talking about!

597
00:44:27,354 --> 00:44:31,191
Do you think she has something to do
with Stein’s disappearance?

598
00:44:32,943 --> 00:44:34,570
She’s defensive.

599
00:44:37,239 --> 00:44:38,907
She’s the primary suspect.

600
00:44:42,077 --> 00:44:43,078
Thank you.

601
00:44:43,829 --> 00:44:48,542
So I talked to two of Stein’s friends
in the Math Club.

602
00:44:49,418 --> 00:44:50,960
- He has friends?
- Mm-hmm.

603
00:44:50,961 --> 00:44:52,378
Well, apparently,

604
00:44:52,379 --> 00:44:55,466
the two I talked to
both claimed to be his friends.

605
00:44:55,507 --> 00:44:59,887
They got along since,
well, Stein’s a bit of a weirdo.

606
00:45:00,220 --> 00:45:02,056
He’s apparently really smart,

607
00:45:02,640 --> 00:45:04,892
that’s why only a few can relate to them.

608
00:45:05,893 --> 00:45:07,061
But...

609
00:45:07,102 --> 00:45:09,562
they did mention
something really interesting,

610
00:45:09,563 --> 00:45:11,315
that I think is worth noting.

611
00:45:11,774 --> 00:45:13,108
They said,

612
00:45:13,525 --> 00:45:16,654
when they talk, they speak in codes.

613
00:45:17,404 --> 00:45:18,739
What sort of codes?

614
00:45:19,490 --> 00:45:22,241
Sometimes it’s a series of numbers.

615
00:45:22,242 --> 00:45:26,413
But usually,
it’s Morse code, dots and dashes.

616
00:45:26,705 --> 00:45:27,914
And I quote,

617
00:45:27,915 --> 00:45:30,667
"If our phone gets stolen,

618
00:45:30,668 --> 00:45:34,004
someone gossiping might read
our conversation.

619
00:45:34,046 --> 00:45:36,924
When we talk in codes,
they can’t understand."

620
00:45:38,384 --> 00:45:39,593
Interesting.

621
00:45:40,177 --> 00:45:42,930
I wonder what they’re talking about?

622
00:45:43,013 --> 00:45:45,349
Why does it have to be encrypted?

623
00:45:45,849 --> 00:45:48,310
Is it really that confidential?

624
00:45:49,144 --> 00:45:51,230
It’s probably their protection,

625
00:45:51,522 --> 00:45:53,399
from the likes of Chad Ellison.

626
00:45:53,816 --> 00:45:54,983
I get him.

627
00:45:55,317 --> 00:45:56,777
Chad Ellison?

628
00:45:57,069 --> 00:45:59,238
You mean Charles Meliton?

629
00:45:59,822 --> 00:46:01,490
Yeah, whatever. That one.

630
00:46:02,157 --> 00:46:03,742
Oh, Loki...

631
00:46:04,493 --> 00:46:05,577
But,

632
00:46:05,828 --> 00:46:08,037
if they’re hiding something like that,

633
00:46:08,038 --> 00:46:11,291
it means there’s something
they really don’t want the public to know.

634
00:46:12,751 --> 00:46:14,712
Everybody has a secret, Lorelei.

635
00:46:15,129 --> 00:46:17,463
The victim is probably the kind of person

636
00:46:17,464 --> 00:46:21,760
who doesn’t like to share anything
about their private life.

637
00:46:23,220 --> 00:46:26,598
Do you think Moriarty
has something to do with this?

638
00:46:27,933 --> 00:46:29,184
I don’t know.

639
00:46:29,435 --> 00:46:31,145
Maybe he’s gotten bored.

640
00:46:32,229 --> 00:46:33,397
Come in!

641
00:46:34,773 --> 00:46:36,358
Oh, Professor Morayta!

642
00:46:36,650 --> 00:46:38,276
Sorry to bother you.

643
00:46:38,277 --> 00:46:41,028
Good news, Stein just texted,

644
00:46:41,029 --> 00:46:42,530
he said not to worry.

645
00:46:42,531 --> 00:46:45,492
He just had to attend to an emergency,
so he didn’t go to school.

646
00:46:52,750 --> 00:46:54,960
Sorry if I bothered you earlier,

647
00:46:55,294 --> 00:46:56,837
but, still, thank you very much.

648
00:46:57,254 --> 00:46:59,006
I should have waited for his reply.

649
00:46:59,214 --> 00:47:00,591
No problem, sir.

650
00:47:01,216 --> 00:47:02,300
See you in class.

651
00:47:02,301 --> 00:47:03,927
- See you.
- Loki.

652
00:47:06,013 --> 00:47:09,516
Well, I guess that’s a case closed.

653
00:47:10,768 --> 00:47:11,769
For now.

654
00:47:24,364 --> 00:47:26,449
- He's taking forever, Rosetta.
- He's taking so long.

655
00:47:26,450 --> 00:47:29,410
- He'll come. He'll come.
- I’ve been waiting so long.

656
00:47:29,411 --> 00:47:30,661
Maybe he got scared.

657
00:47:30,662 --> 00:47:33,581
- No. He'll come. There! They're here!
- Hello, Rosetta!

658
00:47:33,582 --> 00:47:35,458
- There! There it is! There!
- Alright.

659
00:47:35,459 --> 00:47:38,420
Rosetta, sorry, we're late.

660
00:47:38,545 --> 00:47:40,631
We thought you weren’t coming.

661
00:47:41,089 --> 00:47:43,717
Didn’t your last class end early?

662
00:47:45,469 --> 00:47:51,015
It’s because of Loki.
His class ended late, so I had to wait.

663
00:47:51,016 --> 00:47:54,852
- What the...
- Oh, okay. It’s fine! Come on!

664
00:47:54,853 --> 00:47:57,897
They’re just scared.
They don’t want to come.

665
00:47:57,898 --> 00:47:59,358
Here, grab it.

666
00:48:00,943 --> 00:48:02,735
- That’s it!
- Let's go?

667
00:48:02,736 --> 00:48:05,446
- Let's go! Game!
- Alright!

668
00:48:05,447 --> 00:48:07,533
- Game? Game!
- Let's go. Okay.

669
00:48:08,075 --> 00:48:09,951
- Let's go. I'll go first.
- Over there.

670
00:48:09,952 --> 00:48:11,869
- Come on, let’s go!
- You go first!

671
00:48:11,870 --> 00:48:14,121
- Alright!
- Alright!

672
00:48:14,122 --> 00:48:19,127
Guys, we’re coming in.
We’re at the abandoned building.

673
00:48:19,336 --> 00:48:22,464
I’m freaked out. Here they are.

674
00:48:22,548 --> 00:48:23,673
This is my squad.

675
00:48:23,674 --> 00:48:27,553
- Guys, smile at the camera. Let's go.
- It's so dark here.

676
00:48:28,345 --> 00:48:30,389
Wait, wait, Rosetta!

677
00:48:30,472 --> 00:48:33,058
Let’s do a sandwich formation.

678
00:48:33,642 --> 00:48:35,309
I’ll go first,

679
00:48:35,310 --> 00:48:39,565
you’re behind me,
and the other two take the back.

680
00:48:39,606 --> 00:48:42,568
To keep our guests safe.

681
00:48:42,818 --> 00:48:44,277
We don’t know,

682
00:48:44,278 --> 00:48:46,446
one of them might pee from fear.

683
00:48:48,615 --> 00:48:51,076
So loud! Go ahead, you first!

684
00:48:51,577 --> 00:48:52,786
Andrew, right?

685
00:48:53,453 --> 00:48:55,747
I heard you wet your pants
the last time you were here.

686
00:48:56,206 --> 00:48:57,833
You know, you’re spreading fake news.

687
00:48:58,292 --> 00:49:00,210
It was just water that spilled on me.

688
00:49:02,462 --> 00:49:04,381
Game. Let’s get serious.

689
00:49:08,719 --> 00:49:12,471
- This place is crazy, guys!
- Wild!

690
00:49:12,472 --> 00:49:14,349
So creepy in here.

691
00:49:15,517 --> 00:49:17,769
- Let’s go over there.
- It's so messy.

692
00:49:21,273 --> 00:49:22,691
Maybe it's here.

693
00:49:23,692 --> 00:49:24,860
Wait.

694
00:49:24,985 --> 00:49:26,862
I think there's something in the hole.

695
00:49:29,406 --> 00:49:30,991
Hold on, let me check.

696
00:49:31,074 --> 00:49:33,201
Wait, wait, wait! What are you gonna do?

697
00:49:33,243 --> 00:49:35,370
- I’m just checking.
- You might get hurt later.

698
00:49:35,412 --> 00:49:37,789
No, I’ll just check. There’s something.

699
00:49:38,290 --> 00:49:39,458
Wait.

700
00:49:40,208 --> 00:49:41,501
Andrew!

701
00:49:41,585 --> 00:49:44,296
No, just stay there. I’ll just check.

702
00:49:44,421 --> 00:49:47,173
- If we get haunted...
- Andrew, come on! You might get hurt!

703
00:49:47,174 --> 00:49:49,383
- No, I’ll just check. Stay right there.
- Don’t do it.

704
00:49:49,384 --> 00:49:50,760
What's gotten into Andrew?

705
00:49:50,761 --> 00:49:52,637
- Don't do it.
- Andrew!

706
00:49:52,638 --> 00:49:53,638
Hey!

707
00:49:53,639 --> 00:49:55,473
- Andrew!
- Andrew!

708
00:49:55,474 --> 00:49:56,725
I'll just check. Wait.

709
00:49:57,601 --> 00:49:59,226
I'm getting scared.

710
00:49:59,227 --> 00:50:00,896
Oh, there! There!

711
00:50:03,023 --> 00:50:05,359
Andrew! What's going on with you?

712
00:50:05,442 --> 00:50:06,944
- Andrew!
- Help me!

713
00:50:07,569 --> 00:50:09,278
Help me! Hurry! Help me!

714
00:50:09,279 --> 00:50:11,155
Help me! Hurry! Help me!

715
00:50:11,156 --> 00:50:13,658
- Come on!
- Help me!

716
00:50:13,659 --> 00:50:16,078
- Loki! Help them!
- Help me!

717
00:50:17,162 --> 00:50:19,705
- Hey! Guys, come on!
- So here we go. Let's follow Loki.

718
00:50:19,706 --> 00:50:21,540
- Oh, no. We're doomed.
- Hurry!

719
00:50:21,541 --> 00:50:24,335
Help! Help!

720
00:50:24,336 --> 00:50:27,380
- Help!
- Come on!

721
00:50:27,381 --> 00:50:29,131
- I'm getting scared!
- Please!

722
00:50:29,132 --> 00:50:32,552
- Help me!
- Come on!

723
00:50:33,387 --> 00:50:35,472
Help me! Come on!

724
00:50:40,978 --> 00:50:43,063
Hurry! What, guys?

725
00:50:48,610 --> 00:50:49,653
What was that?

726
00:50:52,072 --> 00:50:53,906
- I'm not doing this!
- Did you see that?

727
00:50:53,907 --> 00:50:55,367
Someone just went through there!

728
00:50:56,827 --> 00:50:57,869
Did you see that?

729
00:50:57,995 --> 00:50:59,715
I told you!
I don’t want to be here anymore!

730
00:50:59,913 --> 00:51:01,707
The next time you attempt to fool us,

731
00:51:02,040 --> 00:51:03,291
make sure it works.

732
00:51:04,835 --> 00:51:06,585
He's such a killjoy.

733
00:51:06,586 --> 00:51:09,006
Oh, come on! You’re so hard to please!

734
00:51:09,131 --> 00:51:10,548
You’re so corny, dude!

735
00:51:10,549 --> 00:51:11,591
Exactly.

736
00:51:11,883 --> 00:51:14,136
Come on. That's so corny.

737
00:51:14,636 --> 00:51:16,221
If that touches you...

738
00:51:16,304 --> 00:51:17,784
- I’ll go first.
- You go first, Andrew.

739
00:51:18,306 --> 00:51:19,682
Let’s go, guys!

740
00:51:19,683 --> 00:51:20,851
You're the sacrifice.

741
00:51:21,393 --> 00:51:24,146
Guys, this place is super creepy.

742
00:51:24,604 --> 00:51:27,691
But I really have no idea
what that jerk is saying.

743
00:51:27,941 --> 00:51:29,651
This place is really creepy.

744
00:51:30,819 --> 00:51:34,614
I've already made my assessment
that ghosts don’t ex...

745
00:51:36,533 --> 00:51:38,576
- Hey, come here.
- So, guys.

746
00:51:38,577 --> 00:51:43,205
We’re now on the 2nd floor,
where we heard the knocking and rustling.

747
00:51:43,206 --> 00:51:45,125
So now we're just waiting...

748
00:51:47,127 --> 00:51:48,462
- Hey.
- It's so dark.

749
00:51:50,672 --> 00:51:52,590
- There!
- Hey!

750
00:51:52,591 --> 00:51:54,551
Did you hear that? Did you hear that?

751
00:51:54,593 --> 00:51:57,095
- Did you hear that?
- Yes, I heard that.

752
00:51:57,137 --> 00:51:58,638
Loki, how about you?

753
00:52:00,766 --> 00:52:02,601
You said that there were three knocks

754
00:52:02,642 --> 00:52:04,227
before the scratches.

755
00:52:04,644 --> 00:52:06,396
All I heard were the knocks.

756
00:52:08,315 --> 00:52:09,857
Maybe...

757
00:52:09,858 --> 00:52:11,568
maybe it can't decide.

758
00:52:11,693 --> 00:52:13,527
That could still change. Who knows?

759
00:52:13,528 --> 00:52:15,113
Maybe it's indecisive.

760
00:52:15,655 --> 00:52:16,656
Right?

761
00:52:18,575 --> 00:52:20,035
There it is, guys.

762
00:52:21,411 --> 00:52:24,664
We’ll finally see what we’re looking for.

763
00:52:29,169 --> 00:52:30,587
Look.

764
00:52:30,921 --> 00:52:34,049
It’s like… the painting is moving.

765
00:52:34,549 --> 00:52:35,717
Oh, jeez!

766
00:52:36,093 --> 00:52:37,344
That's true!

767
00:52:43,683 --> 00:52:45,059
Just kidding!

768
00:52:45,060 --> 00:52:47,395
I just feel like
the background music fits.

769
00:52:47,896 --> 00:52:51,357
- He'll get karma.
- That fast?

770
00:52:51,358 --> 00:52:53,860
Hey, wait.

771
00:52:55,403 --> 00:52:56,488
What's that?

772
00:53:04,621 --> 00:53:07,082
I don't want anymore!
I don't want anymore!

773
00:53:08,041 --> 00:53:09,543
Someone's inside!

774
00:53:10,460 --> 00:53:12,379
This place has a rodent problem,

775
00:53:12,963 --> 00:53:14,381
but as you can see...

776
00:53:15,632 --> 00:53:16,800
no ghosts.

777
00:53:16,925 --> 00:53:19,094
No, no. There's really something.

778
00:53:19,136 --> 00:53:22,138
Promise. Let's try upstairs. Promise.

779
00:53:22,139 --> 00:53:23,723
- Come on. Come on.
- One more chance.

780
00:53:24,474 --> 00:53:26,601
- Promise, there's something.
- Let's go upstairs.

781
00:53:27,727 --> 00:53:30,980
- Let's go. Don't be scared.
- Come on, let's go.

782
00:53:30,981 --> 00:53:32,898
- Let's go upstairs.
- Let's go.

783
00:53:32,899 --> 00:53:36,610
- There we go! Let's go!
- Come on.

784
00:53:36,611 --> 00:53:38,612
- Come on! Come on!
- I'll be your camera man for now.

785
00:53:38,613 --> 00:53:39,864
Oh, did you hear that?

786
00:53:39,865 --> 00:53:42,908
- Huh? There's nothing.
- I told you it's true.

787
00:53:42,909 --> 00:53:45,578
That’s what we heard
last time we came here.

788
00:53:45,579 --> 00:53:47,372
Yeah, this is the place.

789
00:53:47,414 --> 00:53:50,583
Hey! Whoever you are, show yourself!

790
00:53:50,584 --> 00:53:53,169
- Who are you talking to?
- Hey, bro. Don't be like that!

791
00:53:53,170 --> 00:53:55,046
You want me to get you possessed?

792
00:53:55,213 --> 00:53:57,132
Oh, why me?

793
00:53:59,759 --> 00:54:01,303
Is anyone here?

794
00:54:02,429 --> 00:54:03,930
If you can’t speak...

795
00:54:04,639 --> 00:54:05,931
answer in the way that you know.

796
00:54:05,932 --> 00:54:08,435
- Hey, Loki!
- Hey, what are you doing?

797
00:54:10,061 --> 00:54:11,479
Communicating.

798
00:54:11,521 --> 00:54:12,898
To ghosts?

799
00:54:14,816 --> 00:54:17,527
- Now you believe.
- You’re a believer now?

800
00:54:18,111 --> 00:54:22,490
I'm so proud.
I'm really proud. I'm gonna cry.

801
00:54:22,824 --> 00:54:24,492
As I’ve said before,

802
00:54:25,035 --> 00:54:26,870
ghosts don’t exist.

803
00:54:29,831 --> 00:54:31,583
You’re trying to communicate, aren’t you?

804
00:54:35,795 --> 00:54:39,257
We were here
when we heard the rustling, right?

805
00:54:40,550 --> 00:54:41,801
There!

806
00:54:53,438 --> 00:54:55,732
The ghost might be here, guys.

807
00:55:01,780 --> 00:55:03,197
I don’t know.

808
00:55:03,198 --> 00:55:05,384
- Maybe there really is something.
- What are these guys doing?

809
00:55:05,408 --> 00:55:07,076
- Why did they stop?
- Let's just try.

810
00:55:07,077 --> 00:55:09,371
- Loki can handle it.
- Loki, huh.

811
00:55:09,537 --> 00:55:10,830
I knew it!

812
00:55:12,749 --> 00:55:14,417
Knocks and scratches,

813
00:55:15,001 --> 00:55:16,670
dots and dashes.

814
00:55:19,130 --> 00:55:20,507
Are you rapping?

815
00:55:23,802 --> 00:55:26,554
- What are you saying?
- What was that?

816
00:55:33,979 --> 00:55:36,939
- Just go ahead.
- Okay, I’ll come.

817
00:55:36,940 --> 00:55:40,902
- You go first! Come on.
- Let's go.

818
00:55:41,569 --> 00:55:43,280
Why are we here?

819
00:55:43,571 --> 00:55:44,948
What's going on?

820
00:55:45,365 --> 00:55:47,200
You still don’t get it, Lorelei.

821
00:55:47,659 --> 00:55:50,412
- Someone answered, "Yes."
- Huh?

822
00:55:50,912 --> 00:55:53,748
I didn’t hear anyone answer "Yes."

823
00:55:53,915 --> 00:55:56,001
- Just some rustling.
- I’ll explain later.

824
00:55:56,501 --> 00:55:58,086
Let's find him first.

825
00:55:58,628 --> 00:55:59,921
Who?

826
00:56:00,630 --> 00:56:02,173
If you can hear me,

827
00:56:02,674 --> 00:56:03,925
knock.

828
00:56:04,384 --> 00:56:06,011
So we know where you are.

829
00:56:11,057 --> 00:56:12,100
What's that?

830
00:56:14,102 --> 00:56:15,228
Where's that?

831
00:56:18,606 --> 00:56:20,859
What’s that? Where’s it coming from?

832
00:56:23,820 --> 00:56:25,655
- Over there?
- Yeah.

833
00:56:26,156 --> 00:56:28,366
Guys, it's so creepy.

834
00:56:30,785 --> 00:56:34,789
Hey, don't open it. Loki!

835
00:56:38,251 --> 00:56:39,794
Here we go, here we go.

836
00:56:40,211 --> 00:56:41,504
Stand next to me.

837
00:56:49,304 --> 00:56:50,597
Ouch!

838
00:56:51,681 --> 00:56:53,141
- What's your problem?
- Hey.

839
00:56:53,391 --> 00:56:56,644
What are you gonna do
with that, Loki? Loki!

840
00:57:01,858 --> 00:57:04,986
- What's that? What are you doing?
- What's that?

841
00:57:14,704 --> 00:57:15,747
Hey.

842
00:57:16,915 --> 00:57:18,041
Shoot.

843
00:57:19,834 --> 00:57:21,461
Was he possessed?

844
00:57:25,465 --> 00:57:26,508
Hey.

845
00:57:27,300 --> 00:57:29,135
Man, are you okay?

846
00:57:30,428 --> 00:57:31,513
Man!

847
00:57:37,018 --> 00:57:38,520
What happened?

848
00:57:39,104 --> 00:57:40,396
Hey, are you okay?

849
00:57:40,397 --> 00:57:42,357
- Wake up! Wake up!
- Hey, wake up!

850
00:57:46,027 --> 00:57:48,822
Exactly, that’s why you’re looking pale.

851
00:57:49,697 --> 00:57:51,824
- Be careful.
- Let's just pray.

852
00:57:51,825 --> 00:57:53,242
You're next.

853
00:57:53,243 --> 00:57:55,869
Foul! No way, bro.

854
00:57:55,870 --> 00:57:58,998
- Let me copy, okay?
- You're next.

855
00:58:07,006 --> 00:58:08,842
I wish it was always like this.

856
00:58:10,051 --> 00:58:16,975
Before the tragedy occurs,
we can stop it and save even more people.

857
00:58:19,227 --> 00:58:20,520
I wish.

858
00:58:22,188 --> 00:58:23,982
But that’s not always the case.

859
00:58:24,899 --> 00:58:26,401
I know that.

860
00:58:27,235 --> 00:58:30,697
I just want to savor this feeling.

861
00:58:32,282 --> 00:58:35,076
It feels so good
to be able to save a life.

862
00:58:39,414 --> 00:58:42,167
Wait, before we go home,

863
00:58:42,500 --> 00:58:48,256
can you explain to me how you knew
it was Stein Alberts and not a ghost?

864
00:58:48,590 --> 00:58:52,384
Do you remember Stein’s
two nerdy friends you talked to yesterday?

865
00:58:52,385 --> 00:58:53,428
Mm-hmm.

866
00:58:53,803 --> 00:58:56,347
Stein communicates with them
through codes,

867
00:58:57,015 --> 00:58:58,433
sometimes dots,

868
00:58:58,892 --> 00:59:00,351
sometimes dashes.

869
00:59:01,352 --> 00:59:02,729
It’s Morse code.

870
00:59:03,354 --> 00:59:07,775
A sequence of short and long signals
called dots and dashes

871
00:59:08,193 --> 00:59:12,197
where every dot, dash,
or sequence of the two

872
00:59:12,864 --> 00:59:14,365
represents a letter.

873
00:59:20,914 --> 00:59:22,123
There!

874
00:59:22,957 --> 00:59:24,667
Did you hear that? Did you hear that?

875
00:59:24,918 --> 00:59:28,213
You said that they were three knocks
before the scratches.

876
00:59:28,713 --> 00:59:30,381
All I heard were the knocks.

877
00:59:30,798 --> 00:59:34,760
I noticed the knocking
and rustling patterns

878
00:59:34,761 --> 00:59:36,721
in the video are consistent

879
00:59:37,055 --> 00:59:38,806
and in the abandoned building.

880
00:59:39,641 --> 00:59:41,392
So I thought they meant something.

881
00:59:42,769 --> 00:59:47,315
I think Stein was trying to communicate
with the paranormal believers yesterday.

882
00:59:47,690 --> 00:59:51,528
By sending a series of
knocks and scratches.

883
00:59:51,861 --> 00:59:54,155
Where every knock is a dot,

884
00:59:54,781 --> 00:59:57,450
while every scratch is a dash.

885
00:59:58,284 --> 01:00:00,912
If you convert the signals to Morse code,

886
01:00:01,287 --> 01:00:02,497
three dots,

887
01:00:03,206 --> 01:00:04,499
three dashes,

888
01:00:04,999 --> 01:00:06,626
and another three dots,

889
01:00:07,502 --> 01:00:08,836
it's S-O-S.

890
01:00:08,962 --> 01:00:10,255
In other words,

891
01:00:10,505 --> 01:00:11,923
a distress signal.

892
01:00:12,257 --> 01:00:13,257
Is anyone here?

893
01:00:13,258 --> 01:00:15,008
When I asked if anyone was there...

894
01:00:15,009 --> 01:00:16,134
If you can speak...

895
01:00:16,135 --> 01:00:18,638
It answered three scratches.

896
01:00:19,180 --> 01:00:20,390
But twice

897
01:00:20,848 --> 01:00:24,852
which means two pairs
of three dashes is equivalent to...

898
01:00:25,645 --> 01:00:26,729
"Yes."

899
01:00:27,939 --> 01:00:30,858
That means someone really needs our help.

900
01:00:31,568 --> 01:00:34,862
So what about the message
Professor Morayta received?

901
01:00:35,405 --> 01:00:39,158
If it wasn’t from Stein, who was it from?

902
01:00:40,285 --> 01:00:43,162
It’s probably the person
behind Stein’s kidnapping.

903
01:00:43,663 --> 01:00:47,875
He sent a message
to stop us from looking for Stein.

904
01:00:48,918 --> 01:00:50,336
Let’s be honest...

905
01:00:52,005 --> 01:00:54,591
we both know who’s behind this incident.

906
01:00:57,218 --> 01:01:00,513
This case stands apart
from the ones that came before it.

907
01:01:03,099 --> 01:01:06,018
This time,
we weren’t investigating a murder

908
01:01:06,019 --> 01:01:08,270
to find out who's the murderer.

909
01:01:08,271 --> 01:01:12,525
Instead, we managed to save a life
before tragedy could strike.

910
01:01:16,696 --> 01:01:18,905
The victim, Stein Alberts,

911
01:01:18,906 --> 01:01:21,283
is known in school as a math wizard

912
01:01:21,284 --> 01:01:26,204
who effortlessly and consistently
represents his school in math contests.

913
01:01:26,205 --> 01:01:30,752
He had no idea that his talent
had sparked resentment in someone else.

914
01:01:31,002 --> 01:01:35,965
Despite his unassuming nature,
he still became a victim of violence.

915
01:01:40,345 --> 01:01:42,638
In the process of gathering evidence,

916
01:01:42,639 --> 01:01:45,223
something unexpected happened,

917
01:01:45,224 --> 01:01:48,352
the person
behind Stein’s abduction confessed.

918
01:01:48,353 --> 01:01:51,188
The culprit turned out
to be Monica Segundo,

919
01:01:51,189 --> 01:01:53,191
Stein’s academic rival.

920
01:01:55,902 --> 01:02:02,741
Someone texted me,
saying they could grant a wish for 3,000.

921
01:02:02,742 --> 01:02:07,204
Back then, I wished Stein would disappear.

922
01:02:07,205 --> 01:02:10,165
So I'd be Clark U's Math representative.

923
01:02:10,166 --> 01:02:15,505
I admit I did it,
but I never meant for Stein to get hurt.

924
01:02:23,805 --> 01:02:29,976
Imagine, a person’s life
valued at only 3,000 pesos.

925
01:02:29,977 --> 01:02:32,938
It’s heartbreaking to hear such stories,

926
01:02:32,939 --> 01:02:34,481
and even more painful to know

927
01:02:34,482 --> 01:02:37,901
that someone could act
like a genie granting wishes,

928
01:02:37,902 --> 01:02:40,655
only to exploit another’s emotions.

929
01:02:42,824 --> 01:02:46,494
And yet,
even with the relief of saving a life,

930
01:02:47,203 --> 01:02:49,622
there remains an uneasy feeling,

931
01:02:50,123 --> 01:02:53,959
as if every case, no matter how different,

932
01:02:53,960 --> 01:02:56,587
keeps pulling us back toward one name.

933
01:02:57,505 --> 01:03:00,007
One shadow that looms over it all...

934
01:03:01,175 --> 01:03:02,427
M.

935
01:03:10,143 --> 01:03:12,103
I want to join the Q.E.D. Club!

936
01:03:13,813 --> 01:03:16,315
We don’t take just anyone
as a club member.

937
01:03:16,357 --> 01:03:18,234
Catherine Del Rosario.

938
01:03:18,317 --> 01:03:20,610
But we might not need your help anymore

939
01:03:20,611 --> 01:03:23,989
since this is being treated
as a suspected suicide.

940
01:03:23,990 --> 01:03:25,157
What's this?

941
01:03:25,158 --> 01:03:27,326
Just open it and see for yourself.

942
01:03:27,410 --> 01:03:29,036
A ballpen?

943
01:03:36,002 --> 01:03:37,545
Daniel Geronimo.

944
01:03:39,547 --> 01:03:42,799
Justin Ruiz is my friend,
the guy who jumped.

945
01:03:42,800 --> 01:03:44,217
I need your help.

946
01:03:44,218 --> 01:03:49,056
One of our Photography Club members,
I found her bleeding in our clubroom.

947
01:03:49,390 --> 01:03:51,434
Let the game begin!
